{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775864828201,"sessionID":"ses_286369878ffeE6OIeMzKdjlG75","part":{"id":"prt_d79cad10c0014Q9KJGSwUMpjFG","messageID":"msg_d79cab45f001GSAHZeLmaghFfH","sessionID":"ses_286369878ffeE6OIeMzKdjlG75","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_tool-02b0adc553a14b7bb2deec97f6c8d94d","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/delta-spec.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/delta-spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # delta-spec.md — AR-019: CLI 二进制入口\n2: \n3: ## Module: `github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/cmd`\n4: \n5: ## Delta Overview\n6: \n7: Add 4 CLI binary entry points to the cmd module for the agentcube project. These binaries provide command-line interfaces for interacting with AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter Kubernetes resources via the client-go library.\n8: \n9: ---\n10: \n11: ## Binaries Overview\n12: \n13: The following 4 binaries SHALL be provided:\n14: \n15: | Binary Name | Description | Package Path |\n16: |-------------|-------------|--------------|\n17: | `agentcube` | Main unified CLI with subcommands | `./cmd/agentcube` |\n18: | `agent-runtime` | Dedicated AgentRuntime resource management | `./cmd/agent-runtime` |\n19: | `code-interpreter` | Dedicated CodeInterpreter resource management | `./cmd/code-interpreter` |\n20: | `agentcube-util` | Utility commands: completion, validation, diagnostics | `./cmd/agentcube-util` |\n21: \n22: ---\n23: \n24: ## REQ-001: Main agentcube CLI binary\n25: \n26: ### Requirement: Unified CLI entry point\n27: \n28: System SHALL provide a unified CLI entry point `agentcube` that aggregates subcommands for managing AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter resources.\n29: \n30: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n31: - Binary name: `agentcube`\n32: - Supports global flags for kubeconfig and namespace\n33: - Provides subcommands for runtime management\n34: - Provides subcommands for interpreter management\n35: - Outputs structured JSON/YAML when requested\n36: \n37: **Scenarios:**\n38: \n39: #### Scenario 1.1: Display help information\n40: - **GIVEN** the agentcube binary is installed\n41: - **WHEN** a user runs `agentcube --help`\n42: - **THEN** the binary displays usage information\n43: - **AND** lists all available subcommands\n44: - **AND** shows global flags\n45: - **AND** exits with code 0\n46: \n47: #### Scenario 1.2: Display version information\n48: - **GIVEN** the agentcube binary is installed\n49: - **WHEN** a user runs `agentcube --version`\n50: - **THEN** the binary displays version information\n51: - **AND** includes git commit hash if available\n52: - **AND** exits with code 0\n53: \n54: #### Scenario 1.3: Connect to Kubernetes cluster with custom kubeconfig\n55: - **GIVEN** the agentcube binary is installed\n56: - **WHEN** a user runs `agentcube --kubeconfig=/path/to/kubeconfig runtime list`\n57: - **THEN** the binary uses the specified kubeconfig\n58: - **AND** successfully authenticates to the cluster\n59: - **AND** lists AgentRuntime resources\n60: - **AND** exits with code 0\n61: \n62: #### Scenario 1.4: Use default namespace context\n63: - **GIVEN** the agentcube binary is installed\n64: - **AND** the user's kubecontext has a default namespace\n65: - **WHEN** a user runs `agentcube runtime list`\n66: - **THEN** the binary queries resources in the default namespace\n67: - **AND** displays results\n68: - **AND** exits with code 0\n69: \n70: #### Scenario 1.5: Override namespace with flag\n71: - **GIVEN** the agentcube binary is installed\n72: - **WHEN** a user runs `agentcube --namespace=custom-ns runtime list`\n73: - **THEN** the binary queries resources in the 'custom-ns' namespace\n74: - **AND** displays results\n75: - **AND** exits with code 0\n76: \n77: ---\n78: \n79: ## REQ-002: AgentRuntime management CLI binary\n80: \n81: ### Requirement: Dedicated CLI for AgentRuntime operations\n82: \n83: System SHALL provide a dedicated CLI `agent-runtime` for AgentRuntime resource operations with subcommands for create, get, list, update, delete, and watch.\n84: \n85: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n86: - Binary name: `agent-runtime` (accessible via `agentcube runtime` subcommand)\n87: - Supports CRUD operations on AgentRuntime resources\n88: - Supports watching resource changes\n89: - Validates input manifests before submission\n90: - Provides human-readable and machine-readable output formats\n91: \n92: **Scenarios:**\n93: \n94: #### Scenario 2.1: List AgentRuntime resources\n95: - **GIVEN** a Kubernetes cluster with AgentRuntime resources\n96: - **WHEN** a user runs `agent-runtime list`\n97: - **THEN** the binary retrieves all AgentRuntime resources in the current namespace\n98: - **AND** displays them in tabular format\n99: - **AND** shows name, age, phase, and replicas columns\n100: - **AND** exits with code 0\n101: \n102: #### Scenario 2.2: Get a specific AgentRuntime\n103: - **GIVEN** a Kubernetes cluster with an AgentRuntime named 'test-runtime'\n104: - **WHEN** a user runs `agent-runtime get test-runtime`\n105: - **THEN** the binary retrieves the AgentRuntime\n106: - **AND** displays its full specification\n107: - **AND** includes status information\n108: - **AND** exits with code 0\n109: \n110: #### Scenario 2.3: Create AgentRuntime from manifest file\n111: - **GIVEN** a valid AgentRuntime manifest file at './runtime.yaml'\n112: - **AND** the binary is configured with cluster access\n113: - **WHEN** a user runs `agent-runtime create -f ./runtime.yaml`\n114: - **THEN** the binary validates the manifest\n115: - **AND** submits the resource to the API server\n116: - **AND** displays the created resource\n117: - **AND** exits with code 0\n118: \n119: #### Scenario 2.4: Create AgentRuntime from stdin\n120: - **GIVEN** a valid AgentRuntime manifest\n121: - **AND** the binary is configured with cluster access\n122: - **WHEN** a user runs `cat runtime.yaml | agent-runtime create -f -`\n123: - **THEN** the binary reads from stdin\n124: - **AND** validates the manifest\n125: - **AND** submits the resource to the API server\n126: - **AND** displays the created resource\n127: - **AND** exits with code 0\n128: \n129: #### Scenario 2.5: Update AgentRuntime from manifest\n130: - **GIVEN** an existing AgentRuntime named 'test-runtime'\n131: - **AND** a modified manifest file './updated-runtime.yaml'\n132: - **WHEN** a user runs `agent-runtime update -f ./updated-runtime.yaml`\n133: - **THEN** the binary retrieves the existing resource\n134: - **AND** applies the updates\n135: - **AND** submits to the API server\n136: - **AND** displays the updated resource\n137: - **AND** exits with code 0\n138: \n139: #### Scenario 2.6: Delete AgentRuntime\n140: - **GIVEN** an existing AgentRuntime named 'test-runtime'\n141: - **WHEN** a user runs `agent-runtime delete test-runtime`\n142: - **THEN** the binary prompts for confirmation\n143: - **AND** upon confirmation, deletes the resource\n144: - **AND** displays success message\n145: - **AND** exits with code 0\n146: \n147: #### Scenario 2.7: Delete AgentRuntime without confirmation\n148: - **GIVEN** an existing AgentRuntime named 'test-runtime'\n149: - **WHEN** a user runs `agent-runtime delete test-runtime --force`\n150: - **THEN** the binary deletes the resource without confirmation\n151: - **AND** displays success message\n152: - **AND** exits with code 0\n153: \n154: #### Scenario 2.8: Watch AgentRuntime changes\n155: - **GIVEN** the agent-runtime binary is running\n156: - **WHEN** a user runs `agent-runtime watch`\n157: - **THEN** the binary streams real-time changes\n158: - **AND** displays added, modified, or deleted resources\n159: - **AND** continues until interrupted\n160: - **AND** exits with code 130 on SIGINT\n161: \n162: #### Scenario 2.9: Output JSON format\n163: - **GIVEN** the agent-runtime binary is configured\n164: - **WHEN** a user runs `agent-runtime get test-runtime -o json`\n165: - **THEN** the binary outputs the resource in JSON format\n166: - **AND** the JSON is valid and parseable\n167: - **AND** exits with code 0\n168: \n169: #### Scenario 2.10: Output YAML format\n170: - **GIVEN** the agent-runtime binary is configured\n171: - **WHEN** a user runs `agent-runtime get test-runtime -o yaml`\n172: - **THEN** the binary outputs the resource in YAML format\n173: - **AND** the YAML is valid and parseable\n174: - **AND** exits with code 0\n175: \n176: #### Scenario 2.11: List resources across all namespaces\n177: - **GIVEN** a Kubernetes cluster with AgentRuntime resources in multiple namespaces\n178: - **WHEN** a user runs `agent-runtime list --all-namespaces`\n179: - **THEN** the binary retrieves AgentRuntime resources from all namespaces\n180: - **AND** displays namespace as the first column\n181: - **AND** exits with code 0\n182: \n183: #### Scenario 2.12: Filter resources by labels\n184: - **GIVEN** a Kubernetes cluster with labeled AgentRuntime resources\n185: - **WHEN** a user runs `agent-runtime list -l app=agentcube,env=prod`\n186: - **THEN** the binary filters resources by the specified labels\n187: - **AND** displays only matching resources\n188: - **AND** exits with code 0\n189: \n190: ---\n191: \n192: ## REQ-003: CodeInterpreter management CLI binary\n193: \n194: ### Requirement: Dedicated CLI for CodeInterpreter operations\n195: \n196: System SHALL provide a dedicated CLI `code-interpreter` for CodeInterpreter resource operations with subcommands for create, get, list, update, delete, and watch.\n197: \n198: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n199: - Binary name: `code-interpreter` (accessible via `agentcube interpreter` subcommand)\n200: - Supports CRUD operations on CodeInterpreter resources\n201: - Supports watching resource changes\n202: - Validates input manifests before submission\n203: - Provides human-readable and machine-readable output formats\n204: \n205: **Scenarios:**\n206: \n207: #### Scenario 3.1: List CodeInterpreter resources\n208: - **GIVEN** a Kubernetes cluster with CodeInterpreter resources\n209: - **WHEN** a user runs `code-interpreter list`\n210: - **THEN** the binary retrieves all CodeInterpreter resources in the current namespace\n211: - **AND** displays them in tabular format\n212: - **AND** shows name, age, runtime, and status columns\n213: - **AND** exits with code 0\n214: \n215: #### Scenario 3.2: Get a specific CodeInterpreter\n216: - **GIVEN** a Kubernetes cluster with a CodeInterpreter named 'python-interpreter'\n217: - **WHEN** a user runs `code-interpreter get python-interpreter`\n218: - **THEN** the binary retrieves the CodeInterpreter\n219: - **AND** displays its full specification\n220: - **AND** includes status information\n221: - **AND** exits with code 0\n222: \n223: #### Scenario 3.3: Create CodeInterpreter from manifest file\n224: - **GIVEN** a valid CodeInterpreter manifest file at './interpreter.yaml'\n225: - **AND** the binary is configured with cluster access\n226: - **WHEN** a user runs `code-interpreter create -f ./interpreter.yaml`\n227: - **THEN** the binary validates the manifest\n228: - **AND** submits the resource to the API server\n229: - **AND** displays the created resource\n230: - **AND** exits with code 0\n231: \n232: #### Scenario 3.4: Update CodeInterpreter from manifest\n233: - **GIVEN** an existing CodeInterpreter named 'python-interpreter'\n234: - **AND** a modified manifest file './updated-interpreter.yaml'\n235: - **WHEN** a user runs `code-interpreter update -f ./updated-interpreter.yaml`\n236: - **THEN** the binary retrieves the existing resource\n237: - **AND** applies the updates\n238: - **AND** submits to the API server\n239: - **AND** displays the updated resource\n240: - **AND** exits with code 0\n241: \n242: #### Scenario 3.5: Delete CodeInterpreter\n243: - **GIVEN** an existing CodeInterpreter named 'python-interpreter'\n244: - **WHEN** a user runs `code-interpreter delete python-interpreter`\n245: - **THEN** the binary prompts for confirmation\n246: - **AND** upon confirmation, deletes the resource\n247: - **AND** displays success message\n248: - **AND** exits with code 0\n249: \n250: #### Scenario 3.6: Watch CodeInterpreter changes\n251: - **GIVEN** the code-interpreter binary is running\n252: - **WHEN** a user runs `code-interpreter watch`\n253: - **THEN** the binary streams real-time changes\n254: - **AND** displays added, modified, or deleted resources\n255: - **AND** continues until interrupted\n256: - **AND** exits with code 130 on SIGINT\n257: \n258: #### Scenario 3.7: Output JSON format\n259: - **GIVEN** the code-interpreter binary is configured\n260: - **WHEN** a user runs `code-interpreter get python-interpreter -o json`\n261: - **THEN** the binary outputs the resource in JSON format\n262: - **AND** the JSON is valid and parseable\n263: - **AND** exits with code 0\n264: \n265: #### Scenario 3.8: Filter by runtime type\n266: - **GIVEN** a Kubernetes cluster with CodeInterpreter resources of different types\n267: - **WHEN** a user runs `code-interpreter list --runtime python`\n268: - **THEN** the binary filters resources by the specified runtime type\n269: - **AND** displays only matching resources\n270: - **AND** exits with code 0\n271: \n272: ---\n273: \n274: ## REQ-004: Completion and utility binary\n275: \n276: ### Requirement: Utility binary for shell completion and diagnostics\n277: \n278: System SHALL provide a utility binary `agentcube-util` providing shell completion generation, validation tools, and helper commands.\n279: \n280: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n281: - Binary name: `agentcube-util` (or integrated into `agentcube util` subcommand)\n282: - Generates shell completion scripts for bash, zsh, fish, and powershell\n283: - Provides manifest validation without cluster connection\n284: - Provides dry-run mode for operations\n285: - Includes diagnostic commands for troubleshooting\n286: \n287: **Scenarios:**\n288: \n289: #### Scenario 4.1: Generate bash completion\n290: - **GIVEN** the agentcube-util binary is installed\n291: - **WHEN** a user runs `agentcube-util completion bash`\n292: - **THEN** the binary outputs bash completion script\n293: - **AND** the script is syntactically valid\n294: - **AND** can be sourced by bash\n295: - **AND** exits with code 0\n296: \n297: #### Scenario 4.2: Generate zsh completion\n298: - **GIVEN** the agentcube-util binary is installed\n299: - **WHEN** a user runs `agentcube-util completion zsh`\n300: - **THEN** the binary outputs zsh completion script\n301: - **AND** the script is syntactically valid\n302: - **AND** can be sourced by zsh\n303: - **AND** exits with code 0\n304: \n305: #### Scenario 4.3: Validate AgentRuntime manifest locally\n306: - **GIVEN** a manifest file at './runtime.yaml'\n307: - **WHEN** a user runs `agentcube-util validate -f ./runtime.yaml`\n308: - **THEN** the binary validates against the CRD schema\n309: - **AND** reports any validation errors\n310: - **AND** exits with code 0 if valid, code 1 if invalid\n311: \n312: #### Scenario 4.4: Validate CodeInterpreter manifest locally\n313: - **GIVEN** a manifest file at './interpreter.yaml'\n314: - **WHEN** a user runs `agentcube-util validate -f ./interpreter.yaml`\n315: - **THEN** the binary validates against the CRD schema\n316: - **AND** reports any validation errors\n317: - **AND** exits with code 0 if valid, code 1 if invalid\n318: \n319: #### Scenario 4.5: Validate directory of manifests\n320: - **GIVEN** a directory containing multiple manifest files at './manifests/'\n321: - **WHEN** a user runs `agentcube-util validate -f ./manifests/`\n322: - **THEN** the binary validates all YAML files in the directory\n323: - **AND** reports validation status for each file\n324: - **AND** exits with code 0 if all valid, code 1 if any invalid\n325: \n326: #### Scenario 4.6: Dry-run create operation\n327: - **GIVEN** a valid manifest file at './runtime.yaml'\n328: - **WHEN** a user runs `agentcube-util dry-run -f ./runtime.yaml`\n329: - **THEN** the binary simulates the create operation\n330: - **AND** displays what would be created\n331: - **AND** does not modify cluster state\n332: - **AND** exits with code 0\n333: \n334: #### Scenario 4.7: Diagnose cluster connectivity\n335: - **GIVEN** the agentcube-util binary is installed\n336: - **AND** kubeconfig is configured\n337: - **WHEN** a user runs `agentcube-util diagnose`\n338: - **THEN** the binary checks API server connectivity\n339: - **AND** checks authentication\n340: - **AND** checks CRD availability\n341: - **AND** displays diagnostic report\n342: - **AND** exits with code 0 if all checks pass\n343: \n344: #### Scenario 4.8: Show CRD information\n345: - **GIVEN** the agentcube-util binary is installed\n346: - **AND** connected to a cluster with agentcube CRDs\n347: - **WHEN** a user runs `agentcube-util crd-info`\n348: - **THEN** the binary displays CRD versions\n349: - **AND** displays supported fields\n350: - **AND** displays validation schema\n351: - **AND** exits with code 0\n352: \n353: ---\n354: \n355: ## Integration Scenarios\n356: \n357: ### INT-001: Subcommand delegation from main binary\n358: \n359: - **GIVEN** the agentcube main binary is installed\n360: - **WHEN** a user runs `agentcube runtime list`\n361: - **THEN** the binary delegates to agent-runtime list\n362: - **AND** executes with same flags and arguments\n363: - **AND** returns same result as calling agent-runtime directly\n364: - **AND** exits with same code\n365: \n366: ### INT-002: Shared configuration across binaries\n367: \n368: - **GIVEN** multiple agentcube binaries are installed\n369: - **AND** a kubeconfig file exists at ~/.kube/config\n370: - **WHEN** a user runs agent-runtime list AND code-interpreter list\n371: - **THEN** both binaries use the same kubeconfig\n372: - **AND** both use the same default namespace context\n373: - **AND** both authenticate with the same credentials\n374: \n375: ### INT-003: Error handling with invalid kubeconfig\n376: \n377: - **GIVEN** the agentcube binary is installed\n378: - **AND** kubeconfig points to an inaccessible cluster\n379: - **WHEN** a user runs `agentcube runtime list`\n380: - **THEN** the binary reports connection error\n381: - **AND** displays helpful error message\n382: - **AND** exits with code 1\n383: \n384: ### INT-004: Graceful handling of missing CRDs\n385: \n386: - **GIVEN** the agentcube binary is installed\n387: - **AND** connected to a cluster without agentcube CRDs\n388: - **WHEN** a user runs `agentcube runtime list`\n389: - **THEN** the binary detects missing CRDs\n390: - **AND** displays informative message about CRD installation\n391: - **AND** exits with code 1\n392: \n393: ---\n394: \n395: ## Technical Constraints\n396: \n397: ### Requirement: Language and toolchain\n398: \n399: System SHALL use Go 1.21+ and the following dependencies:\n400: \n401: **Dependencies:**\n402: - `github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/client-go` for API client\n403: - `k8s.io/client-go` for Kubernetes client libraries\n404: - `github.com/spf13/cobra` for CLI framework\n405: - `github.com/spf13/viper` for configuration management\n406: \n407: ### Requirement: Build and installation\n408: \n409: Each binary SHALL be buildable independently via `go build ./cmd/<binary-name>`. Binaries SHALL be installable via `go install` from the repository root.\n410: \n411: ### Requirement: Cross-platform support\n412: \n413: System SHALL support linux, darwin, windows architectures.\n414: \n415: ### Requirement: Client-go integration\n416: \n417: System SHALL use the client-go library interfaces:\n418: - `runtimev1alpha1.AgentRuntimeInterface` for AgentRuntime operations\n419: - `runtimev1alpha1.CodeInterpreterInterface` for CodeInterpreter operations\n420: - REST resource plurals: `agentruntimes`, `codeinterpreters`\n421: \n422: ### Requirement: Error handling\n423: \n424: System SHALL return appropriate exit codes:\n425: - Exit code 0 for successful operations\n426: - Exit code 1 for operation failures\n427: - Exit code 130 for SIGINT (Ctrl+C) interruption\n\n(End of file - total 427 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# delta-spec.md — AR-019: CLI 二进制入口\n\n## Module: `github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/cmd`\n\n## Delta Overview\n\nAdd 4 CLI binary entry points to the cmd module for the agentcube project. These binaries provide command-line interfaces for interacting with AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter Kubernetes resources via the client-go library.\n\n---\n\n## Binaries Overview\n\nThe following 4 binaries SHALL be provided:\n\n| Binary Name | Description | Package Path |\n|-------------|-------------|--------------|\n| `agentcube` | Main unified CLI with subcommands | `./cmd/agentcube` |\n| `agent-runtime` | Dedicated AgentRuntime resource management | `./cmd/agent-runtime` |\n| `code-interpreter` | Dedicated CodeInterpreter resource management | `./cmd/code-interpreter` |\n| `agentcube-util` | Utility commands: completion, validation, diagnostics | `./cmd/agentcube-util` |","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/delta-spec.md","time":{"start":1775864828183,"end":1775864828198}}}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1775864828230,"sessionID":"ses_286369878ffeE6OIeMzKdjlG75","part":{"id":"prt_d79cad129001H6tt6ZPv0J9deu","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"f33c5114db06c230ebdbad281b75532a26b6f114","messageID":"msg_d79cab45f001GSAHZeLmaghFfH","sessionID":"ses_286369878ffeE6OIeMzKdjlG75","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":38149,"input":22975,"output":71,"reasoning":0,"cache":{"write":0,"read":15103}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1775864835020,"sessionID":"ses_286369878ffeE6OIeMzKdjlG75","part":{"id":"prt_d79caebc9001KF2J95R5rIKKdT","messageID":"msg_d79cad15a001Cuwnby82BGdjUL","sessionID":"ses_286369878ffeE6OIeMzKdjlG75","snapshot":"f33c5114db06c230ebdbad281b75532a26b6f114","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775864926679,"sessionID":"ses_286369878ffeE6OIeMzKdjlG75","part":{"id":"prt_d79cc50bd001mCuYZmEDfPUeGG","messageID":"msg_d79cad15a001Cuwnby82BGdjUL","sessionID":"ses_286369878ffeE6OIeMzKdjlG75","type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_tool-8b47d46fdb11442288366de16a90b773","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"content":"# delta-spec.md — AR-020: CLI pack 命令\n\n## Module: `cmd/cli`\n\n## Delta Overview\n\nAdd the `pack` command to the AgentCube CLI for validating and preparing agent workspaces, merging CLI overrides into metadata, optionally generating Dockerfiles, and reporting paths.\n\n---\n\n## REQ-001: Pack command initialization\n\n### Requirement: Pack command registration and default options\n\nSystem SHALL provide a `pack` command that validates and prepares agent workspaces with configurable options.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- Command name: `pack`\n- Supports workspace path specification\n- Supports metadata field overrides via CLI options\n- Provides verbose mode for detailed logging\n- Supports custom output path specification\n\n**Scenarios:**\n\n#### Scenario 1.1: Command registration and default options\n- **GIVEN** the AgentCube CLI Typer application is initialized\n- **WHEN** the user runs `kubectl-agentcube pack` without options\n- **THEN** the system SHALL use these defaults:\n  - `workspace`: `\".\"` (current directory)\n  - `agent_name`: `None`\n  - `language`: `None`\n  - `entrypoint`: `None`\n  - `port`: `None`\n  - `build_mode`: `None`\n  - `description`: `None`\n  - `output`: `None`\n  - `verbose`: `False`\n\n#### Scenario 1.2: Command option validation\n- **GIVEN** the user provides CLI options\n- **WHEN** options include `--workspace`, `--agent-name`, `--language`, `--entrypoint`, `--port`, `--build-mode`, `--description`, `--output`, `--verbose`\n- **THEN** the system SHALL accept all valid option values:\n  - `workspace`: string path to workspace directory\n  - `agent_name`: string or None\n  - `language`: string (python/java) or None\n  - `entrypoint`: string command or None\n  - `port`: integer (1-65535) or None\n  - `build_mode`: string (local/cloud) or None\n  - `description`: string or None\n  - `output`: string path or None\n  - `verbose`: boolean flag\n\n---\n\n## REQ-002: Workspace validation\n\n### Requirement: Workspace structure validation\n\nSystem SHALL validate that the workspace path exists, is a directory, and contains required files for the specified language.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- Validates workspace path existence and type\n- Language-specific file presence checks\n- Clear error messages for validation failures\n\n**Scenarios:**\n\n#### Scenario 2.1: Workspace path exists and is a directory\n- **GIVEN** a valid workspace path\n- **WHEN** `PackRuntime._validate_workspace_structure` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Verify the path exists\n  - Verify it is a directory\n  - Raise `ValueError` with message \"Directory does not exist\" if path does not exist\n  - Raise `ValueError` with message \"Path is not a directory\" if path is not a directory\n\n#### Scenario 2.2: Python workspace validation\n- **GIVEN** `metadata.language == \"python\"`\n- **WHEN** `PackRuntime._validate_python_compatibility` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Search for at least one `*.py` file in the workspace root\n  - Raise `ValueError(\"No Python files found in workspace\")` if no Python files exist\n  - Validate `requirements.txt` exists if specified in metadata\n  - Accept workspace structure as valid if at least one Python file is found\n\n#### Scenario 2.3: Java workspace validation\n- **GIVEN** `metadata.language == \"java\"`\n- **WHEN** `PackRuntime._validate_java_compatibility` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Verify `pom.xml` exists in the workspace root\n  - Raise `ValueError(\"pom.xml not found in Java workspace\")` if missing\n  - Accept workspace structure as valid if pom.xml exists\n\n#### Scenario 2.4: Missing workspace\n- **GIVEN** `workspace_path` does not exist\n- **WHEN** `PackRuntime.pack` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Raise `ValueError` with message indicating directory does not exist\n  - Propagate error to CLI handler which prints error in red\n  - Exit with code `1`\n\n---\n\n## REQ-003: Metadata loading and creation\n\n### Requirement: Metadata file loading and creation\n\nSystem SHALL load existing metadata from workspace files or create new metadata with sensible defaults.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- Supports multiple metadata filename fallbacks\n- Creates new metadata with defaults when none exists\n- Validates loaded metadata against schema\n\n**Scenarios:**\n\n#### Scenario 3.1: Load existing metadata from file\n- **GIVEN** a workspace with existing `agent_metadata.yaml`\n- **WHEN** `PackRuntime._load_or_create_metadata` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Attempt to load `agent_metadata.yaml` first\n  - Fall back to `agent.yaml` if primary not found\n  - Fall back to `metadata.yaml` if previous not found\n  - Parse YAML content into `AgentMetadata` Pydantic model\n  - Validate all fields against Pydantic validators\n  - Return loaded metadata object\n\n#### Scenario 3.2: Create new metadata for new workspace\n- **GIVEN** a workspace without any metadata file\n- **WHEN** `PackRuntime._load_or_create_metadata` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Detect no metadata file exists\n  - Create new `AgentMetadata` instance with defaults:\n    - `agent_name`: inferred from workspace directory name\n    - `language`: `\"python\"` or from CLI option\n    - `entrypoint`: inferred from workspace structure\n    - `port`: `8080`\n    - `build_mode`: `\"local\"`\n  - Return new metadata object\n\n#### Scenario 3.3: Metadata field validation\n- **GIVEN** metadata loaded from YAML file\n- **WHEN** fields violate Pydantic validators\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Reject unsupported `language` values (must be `python` or `java`)\n  - Reject unsupported `build_mode` values (must be `local` or `cloud`)\n  - Reject `port` values outside range 1-65535\n  - Raise validation error with field-specific message\n\n---\n\n## REQ-004: CLI option overrides\n\n### Requirement: Metadata field overrides from CLI options\n\nSystem SHALL apply CLI option overrides to loaded metadata, allowing users to override any metadata field.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- Supports overriding individual metadata fields\n- Validates overridden field values\n- Preserves non-overridden fields\n\n**Scenarios:**\n\n#### Scenario 4.1: Apply agent_name override\n- **GIVEN** loaded metadata with `agent_name = \"old-name\"`\n- **WHEN** user provides `--agent-name \"new-name\"`\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Override metadata.agent_name to \"new-name\"\n  - Keep all other metadata fields unchanged\n\n#### Scenario 4.2: Apply language override\n- **GIVEN** loaded metadata with `language = \"python\"`\n- **WHEN** user provides `--language java`\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Override metadata.language to \"java\"\n  - Validate new language value\n  - Keep all other metadata fields unchanged\n\n#### Scenario 4.3: Apply entrypoint override\n- **GIVEN** loaded metadata with `entrypoint = \"python main.py\"`\n- **WHEN** user provides `--entrypoint \"java -jar app.jar\"`\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Override metadata.entrypoint to \"java -jar app.jar\"\n  - Keep all other metadata fields unchanged\n\n#### Scenario 4.4: Apply port override\n- **GIVEN** loaded metadata with `port = 8080`\n- **WHEN** user provides `--port 9000`\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Override metadata.port to 9000\n  - Validate port is within 1-65535\n  - Keep all other metadata fields unchanged\n\n#### Scenario 4.5: Apply build_mode override\n- **GIVEN** loaded metadata with `build_mode = \"local\"`\n- **WHEN** user provides `--build-mode cloud`\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Override metadata.build_mode to \"cloud\"\n  - Validate build_mode is \"local\" or \"cloud\"\n  - Keep all other metadata fields unchanged\n\n#### Scenario 4.6: Apply description override\n- **GIVEN** loaded metadata with `description = None`\n- **WHEN** user provides `--description \"My custom agent\"`\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Override metadata.description to \"My custom agent\"\n  - Keep all other metadata fields unchanged\n\n#### Scenario 4.7: No CLI overrides provided\n- **GIVEN** loaded metadata with existing values\n- **WHEN** user runs pack without any CLI options\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Keep all metadata fields unchanged\n  - Use existing metadata values\n\n---\n\n## REQ-005: Language-specific processing\n\n### Requirement: Dependency processing for Python and Java\n\nSystem SHALL process language-specific dependency files and store dependency information in metadata.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- Processes Python requirements.txt files\n- Processes Java pom.xml files\n- Validates dependency formats\n- Stores dependency information in metadata\n\n**Scenarios:**\n\n#### Scenario 5.1: Process Python dependencies\n- **GIVEN** a Python workspace with `requirements.txt`\n- **WHEN** `PackRuntime._process_python_dependencies` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Read `requirements.txt` if it exists\n  - Parse each dependency line\n  - Validate dependency format\n  - Store dependency information in metadata\n  - Skip processing if `requirements.txt` does not exist\n\n#### Scenario 5.2: Process Java dependencies\n- **GIVEN** a Java workspace with `pom.xml`\n- **WHEN** `PackRuntime._process_java_dependencies` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Parse `pom.xml` using XML parser\n  - Extract dependency information from `<dependencies>` section\n  - Extract groupId, artifactId, version for each dependency\n  - Store dependency information in metadata\n  - Skip processing if `pom.xml` does not exist\n\n---\n\n## REQ-006: Dockerfile generation\n\n### Requirement: Dockerfile generation for Python and Java\n\nSystem SHALL generate appropriate Dockerfiles for Python and Java workspaces based on metadata and workspace structure.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- Generates valid Python Dockerfiles\n- Generates valid Java Dockerfiles\n- Infers default entrypoints when not specified\n- Skips generation if Dockerfile already exists\n\n**Scenarios:**\n\n#### Scenario 6.1: Generate Python Dockerfile\n- **GIVEN** metadata with `language = \"python\"`\n- **WHEN** `PackRuntime._generate_dockerfile` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Call `_generate_python_dockerfile` to create Dockerfile content\n  - Create Dockerfile content with:\n    - Base Python image (e.g., `python:3.10-slim`)\n    - Work directory setup\n    - Dependency installation from requirements.txt\n    - Application file copying\n    - Entrypoint command from metadata\n  - Write Dockerfile to workspace root\n  - Return path to generated Dockerfile\n\n#### Scenario 6.2: Generate Java Dockerfile\n- **GIVEN** metadata with `language = \"java\"`\n- **WHEN** `PackRuntime._generate_dockerfile` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Call `_generate_java_dockerfile` to create Dockerfile content\n  - Create Dockerfile content with:\n    - Base Java image (e.g., `openjdk:17-slim`)\n    - Work directory setup\n    - Maven build execution (copy pom.xml, run mvn package)\n    - Artifact copying from target directory\n    - Entrypoint command from metadata\n  - Write Dockerfile to workspace root\n  - Return path to generated Dockerfile\n\n#### Scenario 6.3: Infer entrypoint for Python\n- **GIVEN** a Python workspace with `main.py` present\n- **WHEN** `PackRuntime._infer_entrypoint` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Check for `main.py` in workspace root\n  - Return \"python main.py\" if found\n  - Check for other common entrypoints if main.py not found\n  - Return default \"python -m main\" if no specific entrypoint found\n\n#### Scenario 6.4: Infer entrypoint for Java\n- **GIVEN** a Java workspace with compiled JAR\n- **WHEN** `PackRuntime._infer_entrypoint` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Check for `target/*.jar` files\n  - Return \"java -jar target/<jar-name>.jar\" if found\n  - Return default \"java -jar target/app.jar\" if no specific JAR found\n\n#### Scenario 6.5: Skip Dockerfile generation\n- **GIVEN** metadata with existing Dockerfile path\n- **WHEN** `PackRuntime._generate_dockerfile` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Skip Dockerfile generation if one already exists\n  - Return path to existing Dockerfile\n  - Not overwrite existing Dockerfile\n\n---\n\n## REQ-007: Metadata update and save\n\n### Requirement: Metadata persistence\n\nSystem SHALL save updated metadata to the workspace with appropriate formatting and file permissions.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- Saves metadata to `agent_metadata.yaml`\n- Uses appropriate YAML formatting\n- Excludes None values from output\n- Creates parent directories if needed\n\n**Scenarios:**\n\n#### Scenario 7.1: Update pack metadata\n- **GIVEN** processed metadata and generated Dockerfile path\n- **WHEN** `PackRuntime._update_pack_metadata` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Update metadata with Dockerfile information\n  - Store Dockerfile path in metadata\n  - Update pack timestamp in metadata\n  - Save metadata to `agent_metadata.yaml`\n\n#### Scenario 7.2: Save metadata to file\n- **GIVEN** updated metadata object\n- **WHEN** `MetadataService.save_metadata` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Write metadata to `{workspace}/agent_metadata.yaml`\n  - Use YAML format with `default_flow_style=False`\n  - Use `indent=2` for readability\n  - Use `sort_keys=False` to preserve field order\n  - Exclude None fields via `model_dump(exclude_none=True)`\n  - Create parent directories if they don't exist\n\n---\n\n## REQ-008: Output path handling\n\n### Requirement: Custom output path support\n\nSystem SHALL support custom output paths for packaged workspaces, creating directories as needed.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- Uses workspace path as default output\n- Supports custom output path specification\n- Creates output directories if needed\n- Validates output path type\n\n**Scenarios:**\n\n#### Scenario 8.1: Use default output path\n- **GIVEN** a workspace path `/path/to/workspace`\n- **WHEN** user does not provide `--output` option\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Use workspace path as output path\n  - Return `/path/to/workspace` as final output path\n\n#### Scenario 8.2: Use custom output path\n- **GIVEN** a workspace path `/path/to/workspace`\n- **WHEN** user provides `--output /path/to/output`\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Use `/path/to/output` as output path\n  - Create output directory if it doesn't exist\n  - Return `/path/to/output` as final output path\n\n#### Scenario 8.3: Prepare output path\n- **GIVEN** an output path that may not exist\n- **WHEN** `PackRuntime._prepare_output_path` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Check if output path exists\n  - Create directory structure if it doesn't exist\n  - Raise error if path exists but is not a directory\n  - Return normalized absolute path\n\n---\n\n## REQ-009: Success reporting\n\n### Requirement: User-friendly success messages\n\nSystem SHALL display clear, formatted success messages with relevant information when pack completes successfully.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- Displays success message in formatted output\n- Shows agent_name, workspace_path, and metadata_path\n- Uses Rich Progress spinner during processing\n- Supports verbose mode for detailed output\n\n**Scenarios:**\n\n#### Scenario 9.1: Successful pack completion\n- **GIVEN** a valid workspace path\n- **WHEN** `pack` command completes without exception\n- **THEN** the CLI SHALL:\n  - Display success message using Rich console\n  - Show agent_name from metadata\n  - Show resolved workspace_path\n  - Show metadata_path as `{final_workspace}/agent_metadata.yaml`\n  - Use Rich Progress spinner during workspace processing\n  - Display completion status in green\n\n#### Scenario 9.2: Verbose output enabled\n- **GIVEN** user passes `--verbose` flag\n- **WHEN** `pack` command runs\n- **THEN** the CLI SHALL:\n  - Enable detailed logging at DEBUG level\n  - Log each step of the pack process\n  - Show detailed workspace structure information\n  - Show metadata validation results\n  - Show dependency processing details\n  - Show Dockerfile generation progress\n\n---\n\n## REQ-010: Error handling\n\n### Requirement: Comprehensive error handling and reporting\n\nSystem SHALL handle errors gracefully with clear messages and appropriate exit codes.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- Displays error messages in red\n- Shows tracebacks in verbose mode\n- Exits with code 1 on errors\n- Validates input before processing\n\n**Scenarios:**\n\n#### Scenario 10.1: Pack failure with verbose enabled\n- **GIVEN** `PackRuntime.pack` raises an exception\n- **WHEN** user has passed `--verbose` flag\n- **THEN** the CLI SHALL:\n  - Print `Error packaging agent: {e}` in red\n  - Print full exception traceback\n  - Exit with code `1`\n\n#### Scenario 10.2: Pack failure without verbose\n- **GIVEN** `PackRuntime.pack` raises an exception\n- **WHEN** user has not passed `--verbose` flag\n- **THEN** the CLI SHALL:\n  - Print `Error packaging agent: {e}` in red\n  - Not print traceback\n  - Exit with code `1`\n\n#### Scenario 10.3: Invalid JSON in metadata file\n- **GIVEN** a metadata file with invalid YAML syntax\n- **WHEN** `PackRuntime._load_or_create_metadata` attempts to parse\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Raise YAML parsing error\n  - Propagate error to CLI handler\n  - Print error message indicating YAML parsing failure\n  - Exit with code `1`\n\n#### Scenario 10.4: Missing required fields in metadata\n- **GIVEN** metadata loaded without required fields (e.g., agent_name, entrypoint)\n- **WHEN** validation occurs\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Detect missing required fields\n  - Raise validation error listing missing fields\n  - Propagate error to CLI handler\n  - Print error message in red\n  - Exit with code `1`\n\n---\n\n## Integration Scenarios\n\n### INT-001: CLI to PackRuntime Integration\n\n#### Scenario INT-1.1: CLI creates PackRuntime instance\n- **GIVEN** user runs `kubectl-agentcube pack` with options\n- **WHEN** CLI handler processes command\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Create `PackRuntime` instance\n  - Pass `verbose` flag from CLI option\n  - Call `pack()` method on instance\n  - Pass workspace path and options dictionary\n\n#### Scenario INT-1.2: PackRuntime returns result to CLI\n- **GIVEN** `PackRuntime.pack()` completes successfully\n- **WHEN** method returns\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Return dictionary with:\n    - `agent_name`: string\n    - `workspace_path`: Path object\n    - `metadata_path`: Path object\n  - CLI formats and displays result\n  - CLI exits with code `0`\n\n### INT-002: PackRuntime to MetadataService Integration\n\n#### Scenario INT-2.1: Load metadata via service\n- **GIVEN** `PackRuntime._load_or_create_metadata` needs metadata\n- **WHEN** method calls service\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Call `MetadataService.load_metadata(workspace_path)`\n  - Receive `AgentMetadata` object\n  - Handle exceptions if metadata cannot be loaded\n\n#### Scenario INT-2.2: Save metadata via service\n- **GIVEN** updated metadata needs to be persisted\n- **WHEN** `PackRuntime._update_pack_metadata` calls service\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Call `MetadataService.save_metadata(workspace_path, metadata)`\n  - Verify file was written successfully\n  - Handle exceptions if save fails\n\n### INT-003: PackRuntime to Docker Generation Integration\n\n#### Scenario INT-3.1: Dockerfile generation completes\n- **GIVEN** `PackRuntime._generate_dockerfile` is called\n- **WHEN** generation completes\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Return path to generated Dockerfile\n  - Include Dockerfile path in metadata\n  - Continue with rest of pack process\n\n#### Scenario INT-3.2: Dockerfile generation fails\n- **GIVEN** `PackRuntime._generate_dockerfile` encounters error\n- **WHEN** error occurs during generation\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Raise exception with descriptive message\n  - Propagate error to pack method\n  - Handle error at CLI level with appropriate exit code\n\n---\n\n## Technical Constraints\n\n### Requirement: Language and dependencies\n\nSystem SHALL use Python 3.10+ and the following dependencies:\n\n**Dependencies:**\n- `typer[all]>=0.9.0` for CLI framework\n- `pydantic>=2.0.0` for data validation\n- `pyyaml>=6.0` for YAML parsing\n- `rich>=13.0.0` for formatted console output\n- `packaging>=23.0` for version handling\n\n### Requirement: File locations\n\n- CLI command definition: `agentcube/cli/main.py`\n- PackRuntime implementation: `agentcube/runtime/pack_runtime.py`\n- MetadataService implementation: `agentcube/services/metadata_service.py`\n- Metadata model: `agentcube/services/metadata_service.py`\n- Metadata filename: `agent_metadata.yaml`\n\n### Requirement: Exit codes\n\nSystem SHALL return appropriate exit codes:\n- Exit code 0 for successful pack operations\n- Exit code 1 for pack failures\n- Exit code 130 for SIGINT (Ctrl+C) interruption\n\n---\n\n## Testing Requirements\n\n### Unit Test Scenarios\n\n#### Scenario UT-1.1: Test workspace structure validation\n- **GIVEN** a test suite for `PackRuntime._validate_workspace_structure`\n- **WHEN** tests run\n- **THEN** tests SHALL cover:\n  - Valid directory path passes validation\n  - Non-existent path raises ValueError\n  - Non-directory path raises ValueError\n  - Python workspace with .py files passes validation\n  - Python workspace without .py files raises ValueError\n  - Java workspace with pom.xml passes validation\n  - Java workspace without pom.xml raises ValueError\n\n#### Scenario UT-1.2: Test metadata loading\n- **GIVEN** a test suite for `PackRuntime._load_or_create_metadata`\n- **WHEN** tests run\n- **THEN** tests SHALL cover:\n  - Loading existing agent_metadata.yaml\n  - Loading fallback agent.yaml\n  - Loading fallback metadata.yaml\n  - Creating new metadata when no file exists\n  - Invalid YAML raises appropriate error\n  - Invalid metadata values raise validation errors\n\n#### Scenario UT-1.3: Test option overrides\n- **GIVEN** a test suite for `PackRuntime._apply_option_overrides`\n- **WHEN** tests run\n- **THEN** tests SHALL cover:\n  - Single option override\n  - Multiple option overrides\n  - No option overrides\n  - Invalid option values raise errors\n\n#### Scenario UT-1.4: Test Dockerfile generation\n- **GIVEN** a test suite for Dockerfile generation methods\n- **WHEN** tests run\n- **THEN** tests SHALL cover:\n  - Python Dockerfile generation with requirements.txt\n  - Python Dockerfile generation without requirements.txt\n  - Java Dockerfile generation with pom.xml\n  - Java Dockerfile generation without pom.xml\n  - Entrypoint inference for Python\n  - Entrypoint inference for Java\n\n### Integration Test Scenarios\n\n#### Scenario IT-1.1: End-to-end pack for Python agent\n- **GIVEN** a Python workspace with valid structure\n- **WHEN** user runs `kubectl-agentcube pack`\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Successfully validate workspace\n  - Load or create metadata\n  - Process Python dependencies\n  - Generate Dockerfile\n  - Save updated metadata\n  - Display success message with paths\n\n#### Scenario IT-1.2: End-to-end pack for Java agent\n- **GIVEN** a Java workspace with valid structure\n- **WHEN** user runs `kubectl-agentcube pack --language java`\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Successfully validate workspace\n  - Load or create metadata\n  - Process Java dependencies\n  - Generate Dockerfile\n  - Save updated metadata\n  - Display success message with paths\n\n#### Scenario IT-1.3: Pack with custom output path\n- **GIVEN** a valid workspace\n- **WHEN** user runs `kubectl-agentcube pack --output /custom/path`\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Successfully complete pack process\n  - Write metadata to custom output path\n  - Generate Dockerfile in custom output path\n  - Display success message with custom output path\n\n### Error Handling Test Scenarios\n\n#### Scenario ET-1.1: Test error propagation\n- **GIVEN** various error conditions\n- **WHEN** errors occur during pack\n- **THEN** tests SHALL verify:\n  - Missing workspace path raises appropriate error\n  - Invalid language raises validation error\n  - Invalid port raises validation error\n  - Invalid build_mode raises validation error\n  - Missing required metadata fields raise validation error\n  - CLI displays error message in red\n  - CLI exits with code 1\n\n---\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n### Functional Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Pack command accepts all documented options with correct types and defaults\n- [ ] Workspace structure validation correctly identifies valid and invalid workspaces\n- [ ] Metadata loading supports primary and fallback filenames\n- [ ] Metadata creation works for new workspaces\n- [ ] CLI option overrides correctly update metadata fields\n- [ ] Language-specific dependency processing works for Python and Java\n- [ ] Dockerfile generation produces valid Dockerfiles for Python and Java\n- [ ] Entrypoint inference correctly identifies default entrypoints\n- [ ] Metadata saving creates valid YAML with correct formatting\n- [ ] Output path handling supports default and custom paths\n- [ ] Success reporting displays all required information\n- [ ] Verbose mode provides detailed logging\n- [ ] Error handling displays appropriate messages and exits with code 1\n\n### Non-Functional Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Pack command completes within reasonable time for typical workspaces\n- [ ] Memory usage remains reasonable for large workspaces\n- [ ] Path traversal protection prevents unauthorized access\n- [ ] Sensitive information in metadata is handled securely\n- [ ] Error messages are clear and actionable\n- [ ] Unit tests cover all major code paths\n- [ ] Integration tests cover end-to-end scenarios\n- [ ] Error handling tests verify proper error propagation and display\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Notes\n\n### Key Components\n\n1. **PackRuntime** (`agentcube/runtime/pack_runtime.py`)\n   - Main runtime class implementing pack logic\n   - Handles workspace validation, metadata processing, and Dockerfile generation\n\n2. **MetadataService** (`agentcube/services/metadata_service.py`)\n   - Handles metadata loading and saving\n   - Provides validation methods for metadata fields\n\n3. **AgentMetadata** (`agentcube/services/metadata_service.py`)\n   - Pydantic model for metadata validation\n   - Contains all agent configuration fields\n\n4. **Typer CLI framework**\n   - Provides command-line interface definition\n   - Handles option parsing and validation\n\n5. **Rich library**\n   - Provides formatted console output\n   - Supports progress spinners and colored text\n\n### Key Algorithms\n\n#### Workspace Validation Algorithm\n1. Check if workspace path exists\n2. Verify path is a directory\n3. Based on metadata.language or CLI option:\n   - For Python: verify at least one .py file exists\n   - For Java: verify pom.xml exists\n4. Raise ValueError if any validation fails\n\n#### Metadata Loading Algorithm\n1. Attempt to load agent_metadata.yaml\n2. If not found, attempt to load agent.yaml\n3. If not found, attempt to load metadata.yaml\n4. If no file found, create new metadata with defaults\n5. Parse YAML content into AgentMetadata model\n6. Validate all fields using Pydantic validators\n7. Return metadata object\n\n#### Option Override Algorithm\n1. For each CLI option provided:\n   - Check if option value is not None\n   - Validate option value against type and range constraints\n   - Update corresponding metadata field\n2. Return updated metadata\n\n#### Dockerfile Generation Algorithm\n1. Determine language from metadata\n2. Based on language:\n   - For Python: call _generate_python_dockerfile\n   - For Java: call _generate_java_dockerfile\n3. Generate Dockerfile content with appropriate base image and steps\n4. Write Dockerfile to workspace root\n5. Return path to generated Dockerfile\n\n---\n\n## Related Requirements\n\n- **AR-021:** CLI build command (depends on pack command output)\n- **AR-022:** CLI publish command (depends on pack and build commands)\n- **AR-023:** CLI invoke command (depends on publish command)\n- **AR-024:** CLI status command (depends on publish command)","filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/delta-spec.md"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/delta-spec.md","exists":true,"truncated":false},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/delta-spec.md","time":{"start":1775864926527,"end":1775864926676}}}}
